# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aircraft
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] An **adaptive compliant wing** is a wing which is flexible enough for aspects of its shape to be changed in flight.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] Flexible wings have a number of benefits.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] Conventional flight control mechanisms operate using hinges, resulting in disruptions to the airflow, vortices, and in some cases, separation of the airflow.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] These effects contribute to the drag of the aircraft, resulting in less efficiency and higher fuel costs.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] Flexible aerofoils can manipulate aerodynamic forces with less disruptions to the flow, resulting in less aerodynamic drag and improved fuel economy.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] Changing the shape of an aerodynamic surface has a direct effect on its aerodynamic properties.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] According to the flow condition and to the initial shape of the part, each shape variation (curvature, incidence, twist...) can have a different impact on the resulting forces and moments.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] This characteristic is actively pursued in adaptive wings which – by nature of their distributed compliance – can attain shape changes in a continuous, smooth, gap-free manner.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] By altering these geometrical parameters, the forces and moments can be modified, permitting to tailor them to the specific flight condition (e.g. for drag reduction) or to perform maneuvers (e.g. roll).
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] Shape adaptation can be classified according to the motion it enables.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] Changes of the airfoil shapes include altering its twist, and changing its camber and thickness distribution.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] An adaptive compliant wing designed by FlexSys Inc. features a variable-camber trailing edge which can be deflected up to ±10°, thus acting like a flap-equipped wing, but without the individual segments and gaps typical in a flap system.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] The wing itself can be twisted up to 1° per foot of span.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] The wing's shape can be changed at a rate of 30° per second, which is ideal for gust load alleviation.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] The development of the adaptive compliant wing is being sponsored by the U.S.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] Initially, the wing was tested in a wind tunnel, and then a 50-inch (1.3 m) section of wing was flight tested on board the Scaled Composites White Knight research aircraft in a seven-flight, 20-hour program operated from the Mojave Spaceport.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] Adaptive compliant wings are also investigated at ETH Zurich in the frame of the Smart airfoil project.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] The EU-funded Flexop program aims to develop to enable higher wing aspect ratio for less induced drag with lighter, more flexible airliner wings, along developing active flutter suppression for flexible wings.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] Partners include Hungary's MTA SZTAKI, Airbus, Austria's FACC, Inasco of Greece, Delft University of Technology, German aerospace center DLR, TUM, the UK's University of Bristol and RWTH Aachen University in Germany.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] On 19 November 2019, a 7 m (23 ft) span jet-powered UAV demonstrator with an aeroelastically tailored wing for passive load alleviation was flown in Oberpfaffenhofen, Germany, previously flown with a carbon-fiber, rigid wing to establish baseline performance.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] It has a conventional tube-and-wing configuration, unlike the blended wing body of the Lockheed Martin X-56.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] It follows the Grumman X-29 demonstrator in 1984, with more refined fiber orientations.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] The flexible wing is 4% lighter than the rigid one.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] The 54-month, €6.67 million ($7.4 million) project ends in November 2019, followed by the €3.85 million FLiPASED program from September 2019 until December 2022, using all the movable surfaces.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] The glass fiber flutter wing should to be flown in 2020, with unstable aeroelastic modes under 55 m/s (107 kn) that must be actively suppressed.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] With optimized aeroelastic tailoring and active flutter suppression, an aspect ratio of 12.4 could reduce fuel-burn by 5%, and 7% are targeted.
[src:aircraft/adaptive-compliant-wing] FLiPASED is also led by MTA SZTAKI and include partners TUM, DLR and French aerospace research agency ONERA.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In fluid dynamics, **drag**, sometimes referred to as **fluid resistance**, and also known as **viscous force**, is a force acting opposite to the direction of motion of any object moving with respect to a surrounding fluid.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] This can exist between two fluid layers, or between a fluid and a solid surface.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Drag forces tend to decrease fluid velocity relative to the solid object in the fluid's path.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Unlike other resistive forces, drag force depends on velocity.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Drag force is proportional to the relative velocity for low-speed flow and is proportional to the velocity squared for high-speed flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] This distinction between low and high-speed flow is measured by the Reynolds number.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] There are many distinct types of drag caused by different physical interactions between the object and fluid.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Last, in aerodynamics the term "parasitic drag" is often used.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Parasitic drag is the sum of form drag and skin friction drag and is entirely negative to an aircraft, in contrast with lift-induced drag which is a consequence of generating lift.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The effect of streamlining on the relative proportions of skin friction and form drag is shown in the table at right for an airfoil, which is a streamlined body, and a cylinder, which is a bluff body.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Also shown is a flat plate in two different orientations, illustrating the effect of orientation on the relative proportions of skin friction and form drag, and showing the pressure difference between front and back.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] A body is known as bluff or blunt when the source of drag is dominated by pressure forces, and streamlined if the drag is dominated by viscous forces.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] For example, road vehicles are bluff bodies.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] For aircraft, pressure and friction drag are included in the definition of parasitic drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Parasite drag is often expressed in terms of a hypothetical.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] With other parameters remaining the same, as the lift generated by a body increases, so does the lift-induced drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] This means that as the wing's angle of attack increases (up to a maximum called the stalling angle), the lift coefficient also increases, and so too does the lift-induced drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] At the onset of stall, lift is abruptly decreased, as is lift-induced drag, but viscous pressure drag, a component of parasite drag, increases due to the formation of turbulent unattached flow in the wake behind the body.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] For an aircraft at low speed, induced drag tends to be relatively greater than parasitic drag because a high angle of attack is required to maintain lift, increasing induced drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] As speed increases, the angle of attack is reduced and the induced drag decreases.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Parasitic drag, however, increases because the fluid is flowing more quickly around protruding objects increasing friction or drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] At even higher speeds (transonic), wave drag enters the picture.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Each of these forms of drag changes in proportion to the others based on speed.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The combined overall drag curve therefore shows a minimum at some airspeed - an aircraft flying at this speed will be at or close to its optimal efficiency.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Pilots will use this speed to maximize endurance (minimum fuel consumption), or maximize gliding range in the event of an engine failure.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The equivalent parasite area is the area which a flat plate perpendicular to the flow would have to match the parasite drag of an aircraft.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] It is a measure used when comparing the drag of different aircraft.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] For example, the Douglas DC-3 has an equivalent parasite area of 2.20 m2 (23.7 ft2) and the McDonnell Douglas DC-9, with 30 years of advancement in aircraft design, an area of 1.91 m2 (20.6 ft2) although it carried five times as many passengers.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Drag depends on the properties of the fluid and on the size, shape, and speed of the object.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The graph to the right shows how $C_{\rm {D}}$ varies with $\mathrm {Re}$ for the case of a sphere.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Since the power needed to overcome the drag force is the product of the force times speed, the power needed to overcome drag will vary as the square of the speed at low Reynolds numbers, and as the cube of the speed at high numbers.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] It can be demonstrated that drag force can be expressed as a function of a dimensionless number, which is dimensionally identical to the Bejan number.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Consequently, drag force and drag coefficient can be a function of Bejan number.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] As mentioned, the drag equation with a constant drag coefficient gives the force moving through a fluid at a relatively large velocity, i.e. high Reynolds number, Re > ~1000.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The reference area *A* is often the orthographic projection of the object, or the *frontal area,* on a plane perpendicular to the direction of motion.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] For objects with a simple shape, such as a sphere, this is the cross sectional area.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Sometimes a body is a composite of different parts, each with a different reference area (drag coefficient corresponding to each of those different areas must be determined).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In the case of a **wing**, the reference areas are the same, and the drag force is in the same ratio as the lift force.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Therefore, the reference for a wing is often the lifting area, sometimes referred to as "wing area" rather than the frontal area.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] For an object with a smooth surface, and non-fixed separation points (like a sphere or circular cylinder), the drag coefficient may vary with Reynolds number *Re*, up to extremely high values (*Re* of the order 107).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] For an object with well-defined fixed separation points, like a circular disk with its plane normal to the flow direction, the drag coefficient is constant for *Re* > 3,500.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The further the drag coefficient *Cd* is, in general, a function of the orientation of the flow with respect to the object (apart from symmetrical objects like a sphere).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] For example, a car cruising on a highway at 50 mph (80 km/h) may require only 10 horsepower (7.5 kW) to overcome aerodynamic drag, but that same car at 100 mph (160 km/h) requires 80 hp (60 kW).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] With a doubling of speeds, the drag/force quadruples per the formula.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Exerting 4 times the force over a fixed distance produces 4 times as much work.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] At twice the speed, the work (resulting in displacement over a fixed distance) is done twice as fast.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Since power is the rate of doing work, 4 times the work done in half the time requires 8 times the power.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Where $v_{w}$ is the wind speed and $v_{o}$ is the object speed (both relative to ground).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The hyperbolic cotangent also has a limit value of one, for large time *t*.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Velocity asymptotically tends to the terminal velocity *vt*, strictly from above *vt*.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] For objects of water-like density (raindrops, hail, live objects—mammals, birds, insects, etc.) falling in air near Earth's surface at sea level, the terminal velocity is roughly equal to $v_{t}=90{\sqrt {d}},\,$ with *d* in metres and *vt* in m/s.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Terminal velocity for very small objects (pollen, etc.) at low Reynolds numbers is determined by Stokes law.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In short, terminal velocity is higher for larger creatures, and thus potentially more deadly.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] A creature such as a mouse falling at its terminal velocity is much more likely to survive impact with the ground than a human falling at its terminal velocity.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The equation for **viscous resistance** or **linear drag** is appropriate for objects or particles moving through a fluid at relatively slow speeds (assuming there is no turbulence).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Purely laminar flow only exists up to Re = 0.1 under this definition.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In this case, the force of drag is approximately proportional to velocity.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The velocity asymptotically approaches the terminal velocity $v_{t}={\frac {(\rho -\rho _{0})Vg}{b}}$ .
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] For a given b , denser objects fall more quickly.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] For the special case of small spherical objects moving slowly through a viscous fluid (and thus at small Reynolds number), George Gabriel Stokes derived an expression for the drag constant: $b=6\pi \eta r\,$ where r is the Stokes radius of the particle, and $\eta$ is the fluid viscosity.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] For example, consider a small sphere with radius r = 0.5 micrometre (diameter = 1.0 μm) moving through water at a velocity v of 10 μm/s.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Using 10−3 Pa·s as the dynamic viscosity of water in SI units, we find a drag force of 0.09 pN.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] This is about the drag force that a bacterium experiences as it swims through water.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] For Reynolds numbers less than 1, Stokes' law applies and the drag coefficient approaches ${\frac {24}{Re}}$ .
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In aerodynamics, **aerodynamic drag**, also known as **air resistance**, is the fluid drag force that acts on any moving solid body in the direction of the air's freestream flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Alternatively, calculated from the flow field perspective (far-field approach), the drag force results from three natural phenomena: shock waves, vortex sheet, and viscosity.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] When the airplane produces lift, another drag component results.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Induced drag, symbolized $D_{i}$ , is due to a modification of the pressure distribution due to the trailing vortex system that accompanies the lift production.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] An alternative perspective on lift and drag is gained from considering the change of momentum of the airflow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The wing intercepts the airflow and forces the flow to move downward.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] This results in an equal and opposite force acting upward on the wing which is the lift force.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The change of momentum of the airflow downward results in a reduction of the rearward momentum of the flow which is the result of a force acting forward on the airflow and applied by the wing to the air flow; an equal but opposite force acts on the wing rearward which is the induced drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Another drag component, namely wave drag, $D_{w}$ , results from shock waves in transonic and supersonic flight speeds.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The shock waves induce changes in the boundary layer and pressure distribution over the body surface.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Therefore, there are three ways of categorizing drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The pressure distribution acting on a body's surface *exerts* normal forces on the body.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Those forces can be added together and the component of that force that acts downstream represents the drag force, $D_{pr}$ .
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The nature of these normal forces combines shock wave effects, vortex system generation effects, and wake viscous mechanisms.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Viscosity of the fluid has a major effect on drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In the absence of viscosity, the pressure forces acting to hinder the vehicle are canceled by a pressure force further aft that acts to push the vehicle forward; this is called pressure recovery and the result is that the drag is zero.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] That is to say, the work the body does on the airflow is reversible and is recovered as there are no frictional effects to convert the flow energy into heat.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Pressure recovery acts even in the case of viscous flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Viscosity, however results in pressure drag and it is the dominant component of drag in the case of vehicles with regions of separated flow, in which the pressure recovery is infective.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The friction drag force, which is a tangential force on the aircraft surface, depends substantially on boundary layer configuration and viscosity.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The net friction drag, $D_{f}$ , is calculated as the downstream projection of the viscous forces evaluated over the body's surface.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The sum of friction drag and pressure (form) drag is called viscous drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] This drag component is due to viscosity.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The idea that a moving body passing through air or another fluid encounters resistance had been known since the time of Aristotle.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] According to Mervyn O'Gorman, this was named "drag" by Archibald Reith Low.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Louis Charles Breguet's paper of 1922 began efforts to reduce drag by streamlining.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Breguet went on to put his ideas into practice by designing several record-breaking aircraft in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Ludwig Prandtl's boundary layer theory in the 1920s provided the impetus to minimise skin friction.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] A further major call for streamlining was made by Sir Melvill Jones who provided the theoretical concepts to demonstrate emphatically the importance of streamlining in aircraft design.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In 1929 his paper 'The Streamline Airplane' presented to the Royal Aeronautical Society was seminal.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] He proposed an ideal aircraft that would have minimal drag which led to the concepts of a 'clean' monoplane and retractable undercarriage.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The aspect of Jones's paper that most shocked the designers of the time was his plot of the horse power required versus velocity, for an actual and an ideal plane.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] By looking at a data point for a given aircraft and extrapolating it horizontally to the ideal curve, the velocity gain for the same power can be seen.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] When Jones finished his presentation, a member of the audience described the results as being of the same level of importance as the Carnot cycle in thermodynamics.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The interaction of parasitic and induced drag *vs.* airspeed can be plotted as a characteristic curve, illustrated here.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In aviation, this is often referred to as the *power curve*, and is important to pilots because it shows that, below a certain airspeed, maintaining airspeed counterintuitively requires *more* thrust as speed decreases, rather than less.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The consequences of being "behind the curve" in flight are important and are taught as part of pilot training.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] At the subsonic airspeeds where the "U" shape of this curve is significant, wave drag has not yet become a factor, and so it is not shown in the curve.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Wave drag, sometimes referred to as compressibility drag, is drag that is created when a body moves in a compressible fluid and at the speed that is close to the speed of sound in that fluid.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In aerodynamics, wave drag consists of multiple components depending on the speed regime of the flight.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In transonic flight, wave drag is the result of the formation of shockwaves in the fluid, formed when local areas of supersonic (Mach number greater than 1.0) flow are created.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In practice, supersonic flow occurs on bodies traveling well below the speed of sound, as the local speed of air increases as it accelerates over the body to speeds above Mach 1.0.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] However, full supersonic flow over the vehicle will not develop until well past Mach 1.0.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Aircraft flying at transonic speed often incur wave drag through the normal course of operation.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In transonic flight, wave drag is commonly referred to as **transonic compressibility drag**.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Transonic compressibility drag increases significantly as the speed of flight increases towards Mach 1.0, dominating other forms of drag at those speeds.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In supersonic flight (Mach numbers greater than 1.0), **wave drag** is the result of shockwaves present in the fluid and attached to the body, typically **oblique shockwaves** formed at the leading and trailing edges of the body.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In highly supersonic flows, or in bodies with turning angles sufficiently large, **unattached shockwaves**, or **bow waves** will instead form.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Additionally, local areas of transonic flow behind the initial shockwave may occur at lower supersonic speeds, and can lead to the development of additional, smaller shockwaves present on the surfaces of other lifting bodies, similar to those found in transonic flows.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In supersonic flow regimes, **wave drag** is commonly separated into two components, **supersonic lift-dependent wave drag** and **supersonic volume-dependent wave drag**.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The closed form solution for the minimum wave drag of a body of revolution with a fixed length was found by Sears and Haack, and is known as the **Sears-Haack Distribution**.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Similarly, for a fixed volume, the shape for minimum wave drag is the **Von Karman Ogive**.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The Busemann biplane theoretical concept is not subject to wave drag when operated at its design speed, but is incapable of generating lift in this condition.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In 1752 d'Alembert proved that potential flow, the 18th century state-of-the-art inviscid flow theory amenable to mathematical solutions, resulted in the prediction of zero drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] This was in contradiction with experimental evidence, and became known as d'Alembert's paradox.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In the 19th century the Navier–Stokes equations for the description of viscous flow were developed by Saint-Venant, Navier, and Stokes.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Stokes derived the drag around a sphere at very low Reynolds numbers, the result of which is called Stokes' law.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] In the limit of high Reynolds numbers, the Navier–Stokes equations approach the inviscid Euler equations, of which the potential-flow solutions considered by d'Alembert are solutions.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] However, all experiments at high Reynolds numbers showed there is drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] Attempts to construct inviscid steady flow solutions to the Euler equations, other than the potential flow solutions, did not result in realistic results.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The notion of boundary layers—introduced by Prandtl in 1904, founded on both theory and experiments—explained the causes of drag at high Reynolds numbers.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-drag] The boundary layer is the thin layer of fluid close to the object's boundary, where viscous effects remain important even when the viscosity is very small (or equivalently the Reynolds number is very large).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] When a fluid flows around an object, the fluid exerts a force on the object.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] **Lift** is the component of this force that is perpendicular to the oncoming flow direction.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] It contrasts with the drag force, which is the component of the force parallel to the flow direction.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Lift conventionally acts in an upward direction in order to counter the force of gravity, but it may act in any direction perpendicular to the flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] If the surrounding fluid is air, the force is called an aerodynamic force.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] In water or any other liquid, it is called a hydrodynamic force.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Dynamic lift is distinguished from other kinds of lift in fluids.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Aerostatic lift or buoyancy, in which an internal fluid is lighter than the surrounding fluid, does not require movement and is used by balloons, blimps, dirigibles, boats, and submarines.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Planing lift, in which only the lower portion of the body is immersed in a liquid flow, is used by motorboats, surfboards, windsurfers, sailboats, and water-skis.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] A fluid flowing around the surface of a solid object applies a force on it.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] It does not matter whether the object is moving through a stationary fluid (e.g. an aircraft flying through the air) or whether the object is stationary and the fluid is moving (e.g. a wing in a wind tunnel) or whether both are moving (e.g. a sailboat using the wind to move forward).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Lift is the component of this force that is perpendicular to the oncoming flow direction.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Lift is always accompanied by a drag force, which is the component of the surface force parallel to the flow direction.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Lift is mostly associated with the wings of fixed-wing aircraft, although it is more widely generated by many other streamlined bodies such as propellers, kites, helicopter rotors, racing car wings, maritime sails, wind turbines, and by sailboat keels, ship's rudders, and hydrofoils in water.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Lift is also used by flying and gliding animals, especially by birds, bats, and insects, and even in the plant world by the seeds of certain trees.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] While the common meaning of the word "lift" assumes that lift opposes weight, lift can be in any direction with respect to gravity, since it is defined with respect to the direction of flow rather than to the direction of gravity.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] When an aircraft is cruising in straight and level flight, the lift opposes gravity.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] However, when an aircraft is climbing, descending, or banking in a turn the lift is tilted with respect to the vertical.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Lift may also act as downforce on the wing of a fixed-wing aircraft at the top of an aerobatic loop, and on the horizontal stabiliser of an aircraft.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Lift may also be largely horizontal, for instance on a sailing ship.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The lift discussed in this article is mainly in relation to airfoils; marine hydrofoils and propellers share the same physical principles and work in the same way, despite differences between air and water such as density, compressibility, and viscosity.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The flow around a lifting airfoil is a fluid mechanics phenomenon that can be understood on essentially two levels: There are mathematical theories, which are based on established laws of physics and represent the flow accurately, but which require solving equations.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] And there are physical explanations without math, which are less rigorous.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Correctly explaining lift in these qualitative terms is difficult because the cause-and-effect relationships involved are subtle.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] A comprehensive explanation that captures all of the essential aspects is necessarily complex.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] There are also many simplified explanations, but all leave significant parts of the phenomenon unexplained, while some also have elements that are simply incorrect.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] An airfoil is a streamlined shape that is capable of generating significantly more lift than drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] A flat plate can generate lift, but not as much as a streamlined airfoil, and with somewhat higher drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Most simplified explanations follow one of two basic approaches, based either on Newton's laws of motion or on Bernoulli's principle.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] An airfoil generates lift by exerting a downward force on the air as it flows past.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] According to Newton's third law, the air must exert an equal and opposite (upward) force on the airfoil, which is lift.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] As the airflow approaches the airfoil it is curving upward, but as it passes the airfoil it changes direction and follows a path that is curved downward.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] According to Newton's second law, this change in flow direction requires a downward force applied to the air by the airfoil.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Then Newton's third law requires the air to exert an upward force on the airfoil; thus a reaction force, lift, is generated opposite to the directional change.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] In the case of an airplane wing, the wing exerts a downward force on the air and the air exerts an upward force on the wing.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The downward turning of the flow is not produced solely by the lower surface of the airfoil, and the air flow above the airfoil accounts for much of the downward-turning action.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] This explanation is correct but it is incomplete.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] It does not explain how the airfoil can impart downward turning to a much deeper swath of the flow than it actually touches.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Furthermore, it does not mention that the lift force is exerted by pressure differences, and does not explain how those pressure differences are sustained.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Some versions of the flow-deflection explanation of lift cite the Coandă effect as the reason the flow is able to follow the convex upper surface of the airfoil.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The conventional definition in the aerodynamics field is that the *Coandă effect* refers to the tendency of a fluid jet to stay attached to an adjacent surface that curves away from the flow, and the resultant entrainment of ambient air into the flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] More broadly, some consider the effect to include the tendency of any fluid boundary layer to adhere to a curved surface, not just the boundary layer accompanying a fluid jet.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] It is in this broader sense that the Coandă effect is used by some popular references to explain why airflow remains attached to the top side of an airfoil.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] This is a controversial use of the term "Coandă effect"; the flow following the upper surface simply reflects an absence of boundary-layer separation, thus it is not an example of the Coandă effect.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Regardless of whether this broader definition of the "Coandă effect" is applicable, calling it the "Coandă effect" does not provide an explanation, it just gives the phenomenon a name.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The ability of a fluid flow to follow a curved path is not dependent on shear forces, viscosity of the fluid, or the presence of a boundary layer.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Air flowing around an airfoil, adhering to both upper and lower surfaces, and generating lift, is accepted as a phenomenon in inviscid flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] There are two common versions of this explanation, one based on "equal transit time", and one based on "obstruction" of the airflow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The "equal transit time" explanation starts by arguing that the flow over the upper surface is faster than the flow over the lower surface because the path length over the upper surface is longer and must be traversed in equal transit time.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Bernoulli's principle states that under certain conditions increased flow speed is associated with reduced pressure.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] It is concluded that the reduced pressure over the upper surface results in upward lift.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] While it is true that the flow speeds up, a serious flaw in this explanation is that it does not correctly explain what causes the flow to speed up.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The longer-path-length explanation is incorrect.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] No difference in path length is needed, and even when there is a difference, it is typically much too small to explain the observed speed difference.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] This is because the assumption of equal transit time is wrong when applied to a body generating lift.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] There is no physical principle that requires equal transit time in all situations and experimental results confirm that for a body generating lift the transit times are not equal.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] In fact, the air moving past the top of an airfoil generating lift moves *much* *faster* than equal transit time predicts.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The much higher flow speed over the upper surface can be clearly seen in this animated flow visualization.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Like the equal transit time explanation, the "obstruction" or "streamtube pinching" explanation argues that the flow over the upper surface is faster than the flow over the lower surface, but gives a different reason for the difference in speed.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] It argues that the curved upper surface acts as more of an obstacle to the flow, forcing the streamlines to pinch closer together, making the streamtubes narrower.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] When streamtubes become narrower, conservation of mass requires that flow speed must increase.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Reduced upper-surface pressure and upward lift follow from the higher speed by Bernoulli's principle, just as in the equal transit time explanation.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Sometimes an analogy is made to a venturi nozzle, claiming the upper surface of the wing acts like a venturi nozzle to constrict the flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] One serious flaw in the obstruction explanation is that it does not explain how streamtube pinching comes about, or why it is greater over the upper surface than the lower surface.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Another flaw is that conservation of mass is not a satisfying physical reason why the flow would speed up.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Effectively explaining the acceleration of an object requires identifying the force that accelerates it.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] A serious flaw common to all the Bernoulli-based explanations is that they imply that a speed difference can arise from causes other than a pressure difference, and that the speed difference then leads to a pressure difference, by Bernoulli's principle.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] This implied one-way causation is a misconception.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The real relationship between pressure and flow speed is a mutual interaction.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] As explained below under a more comprehensive physical explanation, producing a lift force requires maintaining pressure differences in both the vertical and horizontal directions.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The Bernoulli-only explanations do not explain how the pressure differences in the vertical direction are sustained.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] That is, they leave out the flow-deflection part of the interaction.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Although the two simple Bernoulli-based explanations above are incorrect, there is nothing incorrect about Bernoulli's principle or the fact that the air goes faster on the top of the wing, and Bernoulli's principle can be used correctly as part of a more complicated explanation of lift.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Lift is a result of pressure differences and depends on angle of attack, airfoil shape, air density, and airspeed.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Pressure is the normal force per unit area exerted by the air on itself and on surfaces that it touches.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The lift force is transmitted through the pressure, which acts perpendicular to the surface of the airfoil.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Thus, the net force manifests itself as pressure differences.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The direction of the net force implies that the average pressure on the upper surface of the airfoil is lower than the average pressure on the underside.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] These pressure differences arise in conjunction with the curved airflow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] When a fluid follows a curved path, there is a pressure gradient perpendicular to the flow direction with higher pressure on the outside of the curve and lower pressure on the inside.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The left side of this equation represents the pressure difference perpendicular to the fluid flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] On the right side of the equation, ρ is the density, v is the velocity, and R is the radius of curvature.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] This formula shows that higher velocities and tighter curvatures create larger pressure differentials and that for straight flow (R → ∞), the pressure difference is zero.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The angle of attack is the angle between the chord line of an airfoil and the oncoming airflow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] A symmetrical airfoil generates zero lift at zero angle of attack.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] But as the angle of attack increases, the air is deflected through a larger angle and the vertical component of the airstream velocity increases, resulting in more lift.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] For small angles, a symmetrical airfoil generates a lift force roughly proportional to the angle of attack.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] As the angle of attack increases, the lift reaches a maximum at some angle; increasing the angle of attack beyond this critical angle of attack causes the upper-surface flow to separate from the wing; there is less deflection downward so the airfoil generates less lift.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The maximum lift force that can be generated by an airfoil at a given airspeed depends on the shape of the airfoil, especially the amount of camber (curvature such that the upper surface is more convex than the lower surface, as illustrated at right).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Increasing the camber generally increases the maximum lift at a given airspeed.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Cambered airfoils generate lift at zero angle of attack.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] When the chord line is horizontal, the trailing edge has a downward direction and since the air follows the trailing edge it is deflected downward.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] When a cambered airfoil is upside down, the angle of attack can be adjusted so that the lift force is upward.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] This explains how a plane can fly upside down.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The ambient flow conditions which affect lift include the fluid density, viscosity and speed of flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Density is affected by temperature, and by the medium's acoustic velocity – i.e. by compressibility effects.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Lift is proportional to the density of the air and approximately proportional to the square of the flow speed.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Lift also depends on the size of the wing, being generally proportional to the wing's area projected in the lift direction.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] In calculations it is convenient to quantify lift in terms of a lift coefficient based on these factors.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] No matter how smooth the surface of an airfoil seems, any surface is rough on the scale of air molecules.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Air molecules flying into the surface bounce off the rough surface in random directions relative to their original velocities.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Because the air at the surface has near-zero velocity but the air away from the surface is moving, there is a thin boundary layer in which air close to the surface is subjected to a shearing motion.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The air's viscosity resists the shearing, giving rise to a shear stress at the airfoil's surface called skin friction drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Over most of the surface of most airfoils, the boundary layer is naturally turbulent, which increases skin friction drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Under usual flight conditions, the boundary layer remains attached to both the upper and lower surfaces all the way to the trailing edge, and its effect on the rest of the flow is modest.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Compared to the predictions of inviscid flow theory, in which there is no boundary layer, the attached boundary layer reduces the lift by a modest amount and modifies the pressure distribution somewhat, which results in a viscosity-related pressure drag over and above the skin friction drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The total of the skin friction drag and the viscosity-related pressure drag is usually called the profile drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] An airfoil's maximum lift at a given airspeed is limited by boundary-layer separation.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] As the angle of attack is increased, a point is reached where the boundary layer can no longer remain attached to the upper surface.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] When the boundary layer separates, it leaves a region of recirculating flow above the upper surface, as illustrated in the flow-visualization photo at right.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] This is known as the *stall*, or *stalling*.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] At angles of attack above the stall, lift is significantly reduced, though it does not drop to zero.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The maximum lift that can be achieved before stall, in terms of the lift coefficient, is generally less than 1.5 for single-element airfoils and can be more than 3.0 for airfoils with high-lift slotted flaps and leading-edge devices deployed.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The flow around bluff bodies – i.e. without a streamlined shape, or stalling airfoils – may also generate lift, in addition to a strong drag force.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] This lift may be steady, or it may oscillate due to vortex shedding.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Interaction of the object's flexibility with the vortex shedding may enhance the effects of fluctuating lift and cause vortex-induced vibrations.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] For instance, the flow around a circular cylinder generates a Kármán vortex street: vortices being shed in an alternating fashion from the cylinder's sides.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The oscillatory nature of the flow produces a fluctuating lift force on the cylinder, even though the net (mean) force is negligible.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The lift force frequency is characterised by the dimensionless Strouhal number, which depends on the Reynolds number of the flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] For a flexible structure, this oscillatory lift force may induce vortex-induced vibrations.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Under certain conditions – for instance resonance or strong spanwise correlation of the lift force – the resulting motion of the structure due to the lift fluctuations may be strongly enhanced.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Such vibrations may pose problems and threaten collapse in tall man-made structures like industrial chimneys.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] In the Magnus effect, a lift force is generated by a spinning cylinder in a freestream.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Here the mechanical rotation acts on the boundary layer, causing it to separate at different locations on the two sides of the cylinder.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The asymmetric separation changes the effective shape of the cylinder as far as the flow is concerned such that the cylinder acts like a lifting airfoil with circulation in the outer flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] As described above under "Simplified physical explanations of lift on an airfoil", there are two main popular explanations: one based on downward deflection of the flow (Newton's laws), and one based on pressure differences accompanied by changes in flow speed (Bernoulli's principle).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Either of these, by itself, correctly identifies some aspects of the lifting flow but leaves other important aspects of the phenomenon unexplained.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] A more comprehensive explanation involves both downward deflection and pressure differences (including changes in flow speed associated with the pressure differences), and requires looking at the flow in more detail.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The airfoil shape and angle of attack work together so that the airfoil exerts a downward force on the air as it flows past.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] According to Newton's third law, the air must then exert an equal and opposite (upward) force on the airfoil, which is the lift.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The net force exerted by the air occurs as a pressure difference over the airfoil's surfaces.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Pressure in a fluid is always positive in an absolute sense, so that pressure must always be thought of as pushing, and never as pulling.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The pressure thus pushes inward on the airfoil everywhere on both the upper and lower surfaces.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The flowing air reacts to the presence of the wing by reducing the pressure on the wing's upper surface and increasing the pressure on the lower surface.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The pressure on the lower surface pushes up harder than the reduced pressure on the upper surface pushes down, and the net result is upward lift.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The pressure difference which results in lift acts directly on the airfoil surfaces; however, understanding how the pressure difference is produced requires understanding what the flow does over a wider area.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] An airfoil affects the speed and direction of the flow over a wide area, producing a pattern called a *velocity field*.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] When an airfoil produces lift, the flow ahead of the airfoil is deflected upward, the flow above and below the airfoil is deflected downward leaving the air far behind the airfoil in the same state as the oncoming flow far ahead.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The flow above the upper surface is sped up, while the flow below the airfoil is slowed down.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Together with the upward deflection of air in front and the downward deflection of the air immediately behind, this establishes a net circulatory component of the flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The downward deflection and the changes in flow speed are pronounced and extend over a wide area, as can be seen in the flow animation on the right.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] These differences in the direction and speed of the flow are greatest close to the airfoil and decrease gradually far above and below.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] All of these features of the velocity field also appear in theoretical models for lifting flows.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The pressure is also affected over a wide area, in a pattern of non-uniform pressure called a *pressure field*.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] When an airfoil produces lift, there is a diffuse region of low pressure above the airfoil, and usually a diffuse region of high pressure below, as illustrated by the isobars (curves of constant pressure) in the drawing.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The pressure difference that acts on the surface is just part of this pressure field.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The non-uniform pressure exerts forces on the air in the direction from higher pressure to lower pressure.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The direction of the force is different at different locations around the airfoil, as indicated by the block arrows in the *pressure field around an airfoil* figure.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Air above the airfoil is pushed toward the center of the low-pressure region, and air below the airfoil is pushed outward from the center of the high-pressure region.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] According to *Newton's second law*, a force causes air to accelerate in the direction of the force.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Thus the vertical arrows in the accompanying pressure field diagram indicate that air above and below the airfoil is accelerated, or turned downward, and that the non-uniform pressure is thus the cause of the downward deflection of the flow visible in the flow animation.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] To produce this downward turning, the airfoil must have a positive angle of attack or have sufficient positive camber.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Note that the downward turning of the flow over the upper surface is the result of the air being pushed downward by higher pressure above it than below it.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Some explanations that refer to the "Coandă effect" suggest that viscosity plays a key role in the downward turning, but this is false.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] (see above under "Controversy regarding the Coandă effect").
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The arrows ahead of the airfoil indicate that the flow ahead of the airfoil is deflected upward, and the arrows behind the airfoil indicate that the flow behind is deflected upward again, after being deflected downward over the airfoil.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] These deflections are also visible in the flow animation.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The arrows ahead of the airfoil and behind also indicate that air passing through the low-pressure region above the airfoil is sped up as it enters, and slowed back down as it leaves.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Air passing through the high-pressure region below the airfoil is slowed down as it enters and then sped back up as it leaves.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Thus the non-uniform pressure is also the cause of the changes in flow speed visible in the flow animation.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The changes in flow speed are consistent with *Bernoulli's principle*, which states that in a steady flow without viscosity, lower pressure means higher speed, and higher pressure means lower speed.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Thus changes in flow direction and speed are directly caused by the non-uniform pressure.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] But this cause-and-effect relationship is not just one-way; it works in both directions simultaneously.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The air's motion is affected by the pressure differences, but the existence of the pressure differences depends on the air's motion.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The relationship is thus a mutual, or reciprocal, interaction: Air flow changes speed or direction in response to pressure differences, and the pressure differences are sustained by the air's resistance to changing speed or direction.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] A pressure difference can exist only if something is there for it to push against.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] In aerodynamic flow, the pressure difference pushes against the air's inertia, as the air is accelerated by the pressure difference.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] This is why the air's mass is part of the calculation, and why lift depends on air density.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Sustaining the pressure difference that exerts the lift force on the airfoil surfaces requires sustaining a pattern of non-uniform pressure in a wide area around the airfoil.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] This requires maintaining pressure differences in both the vertical and horizontal directions, and thus requires both downward turning of the flow and changes in flow speed according to Bernoulli's principle.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The pressure differences and the changes in flow direction and speed sustain each other in a mutual interaction.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The pressure differences follow naturally from Newton's second law and from the fact that flow along the surface follows the predominantly downward-sloping contours of the airfoil.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] And the fact that the air has mass is crucial to the interaction.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Producing a lift force requires both downward turning of the flow and changes in flow speed consistent with Bernoulli's principle.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Each of the simplified explanations given above in Simplified physical explanations of lift on an airfoil falls short by trying to explain lift in terms of only one or the other, thus explaining only part of the phenomenon and leaving other parts unexplained.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] When the pressure distribution on the airfoil surface is known, determining the total lift requires adding up the contributions to the pressure force from local elements of the surface, each with its own local value of pressure.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The total lift is thus the integral of the pressure, in the direction perpendicular to the farfield flow, over the airfoil surface.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The above *lift equation* neglects the skin friction forces, which are small compared to the pressure forces.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] By using the streamwise vector **i** parallel to the freestream in place of **k** in the integral, we obtain an expression for the pressure drag *Dp* (which includes the pressure portion of the profile drag and, if the wing is three-dimensional, the induced drag).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] If we use the spanwise vector **j**, we obtain the side force *Y*.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The validity of this integration generally requires the airfoil shape to be a closed curve that is piecewise smooth.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Lift depends on the size of the wing, being approximately proportional to the wing area.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] It is often convenient to quantify the lift of a given airfoil by its *lift coefficient* $C_{L}$ , which defines its overall lift in terms of a unit area of the wing.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Mathematical theories of lift are based on continuum fluid mechanics, assuming that air flows as a continuous fluid.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Because an airfoil affects the flow in a wide area around it, the conservation laws of mechanics are embodied in the form of partial differential equations combined with a set of boundary condition requirements which the flow has to satisfy at the airfoil surface and far away from the airfoil.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] To predict lift requires solving the equations for a particular airfoil shape and flow condition, which generally requires calculations that are so voluminous that they are practical only on a computer, through the methods of computational fluid dynamics (CFD).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Determining the net aerodynamic force from a CFD solution requires "adding up" (integrating) the forces due to pressure and shear determined by the CFD over every surface element of the airfoil as described under "pressure integration".
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The Navier–Stokes equations (NS) provide the potentially most accurate theory of lift, but in practice, capturing the effects of turbulence in the boundary layer on the airfoil surface requires sacrificing some accuracy, and requires use of the Reynolds-averaged Navier–Stokes equations (RANS).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Simpler but less accurate theories have also been developed.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] In principle, the NS equations, combined with boundary conditions of no through-flow and no slip at the airfoil surface, could be used to predict lift with high accuracy in any situation in ordinary atmospheric flight.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] However, airflows in practical situations always involve turbulence in the boundary layer next to the airfoil surface, at least over the aft portion of the airfoil.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Predicting lift by solving the NS equations in their raw form would require the calculations to resolve the details of the turbulence, down to the smallest eddy.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] This is not yet possible, even on the most powerful computer.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] So in principle the NS equations provide a complete and very accurate theory of lift, but practical prediction of lift requires that the effects of turbulence be modeled in the RANS equations rather than computed directly.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] A RANS solution consists of the time-averaged velocity vector, pressure, density, and temperature defined at a dense grid of points surrounding the airfoil.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The amount of computation required is a minuscule fraction (billionths) of what would be required to resolve all of the turbulence motions in a raw NS calculation, and with large computers available it is now practical to carry out RANS calculations for complete airplanes in three dimensions.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Because turbulence models are not perfect, the accuracy of RANS calculations is imperfect, but it is adequate for practical aircraft design.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Lift predicted by RANS is usually within a few percent of the actual lift.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The Euler equations are the NS equations without the viscosity, heat conduction, and turbulence effects.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] As with a RANS solution, an Euler solution consists of the velocity vector, pressure, density, and temperature defined at a dense grid of points surrounding the airfoil.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] While the Euler equations are simpler than the NS equations, they do not lend themselves to exact analytic solutions.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Further simplification is available through potential flow theory, which reduces the number of unknowns to be determined, and makes analytic solutions possible in some cases, as described below.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Either Euler or potential-flow calculations predict the pressure distribution on the airfoil surfaces roughly correctly for angles of attack below stall, where they might miss the total lift by as much as 10–20%.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] At angles of attack above stall, inviscid calculations do not predict that stall has happened, and as a result they grossly overestimate the lift.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] In potential-flow theory, the flow is assumed to be irrotational, i.e. that small fluid parcels have no net rate of rotation.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Mathematically, this is expressed by the statement that the curl of the velocity vector field is everywhere equal to zero.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Irrotational flows have the convenient property that the velocity can be expressed as the gradient of a scalar function called a potential.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] A flow represented in this way is called potential flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] In potential-flow theory, the flow is assumed to be incompressible.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Incompressible potential-flow theory has the advantage that the equation (Laplace's equation) to be solved for the potential is linear, which allows solutions to be constructed by superposition of other known solutions.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The incompressible-potential-flow equation can also be solved by conformal mapping, a method based on the theory of functions of a complex variable.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] A solution of the potential equation directly determines only the velocity field.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The pressure field is deduced from the velocity field through Bernoulli's equation.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Applying potential-flow theory to a lifting flow requires special treatment and an additional assumption.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The solution to this problem is to introduce a branch cut, a curve or line from some point on the airfoil surface out to infinite distance, and to allow a jump in the value of the potential across the cut.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The jump in the potential imposes circulation in the flow equal to the potential jump and thus allows nonzero circulation to be represented.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] However, the potential jump is a free parameter that is not determined by the potential equation or the other boundary conditions, and the solution is thus indeterminate.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] A potential-flow solution exists for any value of the circulation and any value of the lift.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] One way to resolve this indeterminacy is to impose the Kutta condition, which is that, of all the possible solutions, the physically reasonable solution is the one in which the flow leaves the trailing edge smoothly.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] This is potential-flow theory with the further assumptions that the airfoil is very thin and the angle of attack is small.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The linearized theory predicts the general character of the airfoil pressure distribution and how it is influenced by airfoil shape and angle of attack, but is not accurate enough for design work.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] For a 2D airfoil, such calculations can be done in a fraction of a second in a spreadsheet on a PC.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] When an airfoil generates lift, several components of the overall velocity field contribute to a net circulation of air around it: the upward flow ahead of the airfoil, the accelerated flow above, the decelerated flow below, and the downward flow behind.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The circulation can be understood as the total amount of "spinning" (or vorticity) of an inviscid fluid around the airfoil.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The Kutta–Joukowski theorem relates the lift per unit width of span of a two-dimensional airfoil to this circulation component of the flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] It is a key element in an explanation of lift that follows the development of the flow around an airfoil as the airfoil starts its motion from rest and a starting vortex is formed and left behind, leading to the formation of circulation around the airfoil.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Lift is then inferred from the Kutta-Joukowski theorem.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] This explanation is largely mathematical, and its general progression is based on logical inference, not physical cause-and-effect.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The Kutta–Joukowski model does not predict how much circulation or lift a two-dimensional airfoil produces.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Calculating the lift per unit span using Kutta–Joukowski requires a known value for the circulation.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] In particular, if the Kutta condition is met, in which the rear stagnation point moves to the airfoil trailing edge and attaches there for the duration of flight, the lift can be calculated theoretically through the conformal mapping method.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The lift generated by a conventional airfoil is dictated by both its design and the flight conditions, such as forward velocity, angle of attack and air density.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Lift can be increased by artificially increasing the circulation, for example by boundary-layer blowing or the use of blown flaps.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] In the Flettner rotor the entire airfoil is circular and spins about a spanwise axis to create the circulation.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The flow around a three-dimensional wing involves significant additional issues, especially relating to the wing tips.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] For a wing of low aspect ratio, such as a typical delta wing, two-dimensional theories may provide a poor model and three-dimensional flow effects can dominate.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Even for wings of high aspect ratio, the three-dimensional effects associated with finite span can affect the whole span, not just close to the tips.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The vertical pressure gradient at the wing tips causes air to flow sideways, out from under the wing then up and back over the upper surface.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] This reduces the pressure gradient at the wing tip, therefore also reducing lift.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The lift tends to decrease in the spanwise direction from root to tip, and the pressure distributions around the airfoil sections change accordingly in the spanwise direction.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Pressure distributions in planes perpendicular to the flight direction tend to look like the illustration at right.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] This spanwise-varying pressure distribution is sustained by a mutual interaction with the velocity field.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Flow below the wing is accelerated outboard, flow outboard of the tips is accelerated upward, and flow above the wing is accelerated inboard, which results in the flow pattern illustrated at right.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] There is more downward turning of the flow than there would be in a two-dimensional flow with the same airfoil shape and sectional lift, and a higher sectional angle of attack is required to achieve the same lift compared to a two-dimensional flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The wing is effectively flying in a downdraft of its own making, as if the freestream flow were tilted downward, with the result that the total aerodynamic force vector is tilted backward slightly compared to what it would be in two dimensions.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The additional backward component of the force vector is called lift-induced drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The difference in the spanwise component of velocity above and below the wing (between being in the inboard direction above and in the outboard direction below) persists at the trailing edge and into the wake downstream.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] After the flow leaves the trailing edge, this difference in velocity takes place across a relatively thin shear layer called a vortex sheet.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The wingtip flow leaving the wing creates a tip vortex.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] As the main vortex sheet passes downstream from the trailing edge, it rolls up at its outer edges, merging with the tip vortices.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The combination of the wingtip vortices and the vortex sheets feeding them is called the vortex wake.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] In addition to the vorticity in the trailing vortex wake there is vorticity in the wing's boundary layer, called 'bound vorticity', which connects the trailing sheets from the two sides of the wing into a vortex system in the general form of a horseshoe.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The horseshoe form of the vortex system was recognized by the British aeronautical pioneer Lanchester in 1907.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Given the distribution of bound vorticity and the vorticity in the wake, the Biot–Savart law (a vector-calculus relation) can be used to calculate the velocity perturbation anywhere in the field, caused by the lift on the wing.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Approximate theories for the lift distribution and lift-induced drag of three-dimensional wings are based on such analysis applied to the wing's horseshoe vortex system.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] In these theories, the bound vorticity is usually idealized and assumed to reside at the camber surface inside the wing.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Because the velocity is deduced from the vorticity in such theories, some authors describe the situation to imply that the vorticity is the cause of the velocity perturbations, using terms such as "the velocity induced by the vortex", for example.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] But attributing mechanical cause-and-effect between the vorticity and the velocity in this way is not consistent with the physics.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The velocity perturbations in the flow around a wing are in fact produced by the pressure field.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The flow around a lifting airfoil must satisfy Newton's second law regarding conservation of momentum, both locally at every point in the flow field, and in an integrated sense over any extended region of the flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] For an extended region, Newton's second law takes the form of the *momentum theorem for a control volume*, where a control volume can be any region of the flow chosen for analysis.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The momentum theorem states that the integrated force exerted at the boundaries of the control volume (a surface integral), is equal to the integrated time rate of change (material derivative) of the momentum of fluid parcels passing through the interior of the control volume.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] For a steady flow, this can be expressed in the form of the net surface integral of the flux of momentum through the boundary.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The lifting flow around a 2D airfoil is usually analyzed in a control volume that completely surrounds the airfoil, so that the inner boundary of the control volume is the airfoil surface, where the downward force per unit span $-L'$ is exerted on the fluid by the airfoil.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The outer boundary is usually either a large circle or a large rectangle.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] At this outer boundary distant from the airfoil, the velocity and pressure are well represented by the velocity and pressure associated with a uniform flow plus a vortex, and viscous stress is negligible, so that the only force that must be integrated over the outer boundary is the pressure.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The free-stream velocity is usually assumed to be horizontal, with lift vertically upward, so that the vertical momentum is the component of interest.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] For the free-air case (no ground plane), the force $-L'$ exerted by the airfoil on the fluid is manifested partly as momentum fluxes and partly as pressure differences at the outer boundary, in proportions that depend on the shape of the outer boundary, as shown in the diagram at right.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] For a flat horizontal rectangle that is much longer than it is tall, the fluxes of vertical momentum through the front and back are negligible, and the lift is accounted for entirely by the integrated pressure differences on the top and bottom.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] For a square or circle, the momentum fluxes and pressure differences account for half the lift each.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The results of all of the control-volume analyses described above are consistent with the Kutta–Joukowski theorem described above.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Both the tall rectangle and circle control volumes have been used in derivations of the theorem.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] An airfoil produces a pressure field in the surrounding air, as explained under "The wider flow around the airfoil" above.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The pressure differences associated with this field die off gradually, becoming very small at large distances, but never disappearing altogether.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Below the airplane, the pressure field persists as a positive pressure disturbance that reaches the ground, forming a pattern of slightly-higher-than-ambient pressure on the ground, as shown on the right.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] Although the pressure differences are very small far below the airplane, they are spread over a wide area and add up to a substantial force.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] For steady, level flight, the integrated force due to the pressure differences is equal to the total aerodynamic lift of the airplane and to the airplane's weight.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] According to Newton's third law, this pressure force exerted on the ground by the air is matched by an equal-and-opposite upward force exerted on the air by the ground, which offsets all of the downward force exerted on the air by the airplane.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic-lift] The net force due to the lift, acting on the atmosphere as a whole, is therefore zero, and thus there is no integrated accumulation of vertical momentum in the atmosphere, as was noted by Lanchester early in the development of modern aerodynamics.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Modern aerodynamics only dates back to the seventeenth century, but aerodynamic forces have been harnessed by humans for thousands of years in sailboats and windmills, and images and stories of flight appear throughout recorded history including the Ancient Greek legend of Icarus and Daedalus.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Fundamental concepts of continuum, drag, and pressure gradients appear in the work of Aristotle and Archimedes.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In 1726, Sir Isaac Newton became the first person to develop a theory of air resistance, making him one of the first aerodynamicists.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Dutch-Swiss mathematician Daniel Bernoulli followed in 1738 with *Hydrodynamica* in which he described a fundamental relationship between pressure, density, and flow velocity for incompressible flow known today as Bernoulli's principle, which provides one method for calculating aerodynamic lift.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In 1757, Leonhard Euler published the more general Euler equations which could be applied to both compressible and incompressible flows.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The Euler equations were extended to incorporate the effects of viscosity in the first half of the 1800s, resulting in the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The Navier–Stokes equations are the most general governing equations of fluid flow but are difficult to solve for the flow around all but the simplest of shapes.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In 1799, Sir George Cayley became the first person to identify the four aerodynamic forces of flight (weight, lift, drag, and thrust), as well as the relationships between them, and in doing so outlined the path toward achieving heavier-than-air flight for the next century.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In 1871, Francis Herbert Wenham constructed the first wind tunnel, allowing precise measurements of aerodynamic forces.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Drag theories were developed by Jean Le Rond d'Alembert, Gustav Kirchhoff, and Lord Rayleigh.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In 1889, Charles Renard, a French aeronautical engineer, became the first person to reasonably predict the power needed for sustained flight.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Otto Lilienthal, the first person to become highly successful with glider flights, was also the first to propose thin, curved airfoils that would produce high lift and low drag.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Building on these developments as well as research carried out in their own wind tunnel, the Wright brothers flew the first powered airplane on December 17, 1903.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] During the time of the first flights, Frederick W.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Lanchester, Martin Kutta, and Nikolai Zhukovsky independently created theories which connected circulation of a fluid flow to lift.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Kutta and Zhukovsky then developed a two-dimensional wing theory.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Expanding upon the work of Lanchester, Ludwig Prandtl is credited with developing the mathematics behind thin-airfoil and lifting-line theories as well as working with boundary layers.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] As aircraft speed increased designers began to encounter challenges associated with air compressibility at speeds near the speed of sound.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The differences in airflow under such conditions lead to problems in aircraft control, increased drag due to shock waves and the threat of structural failure due to aeroelastic flutter.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The ratio of the flow speed to the speed of sound was named the Mach number after Ernst Mach who was one of the first to investigate the properties of the supersonic flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Macquorn Rankine and Pierre Henri Hugoniot independently developed the theory for flow properties before and after a shock wave, while Jakob Ackeret led the initial work of calculating the lift and drag of supersonic airfoils.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Theodore von Kármán and Hugh Latimer Dryden introduced the term transonic to describe flow speeds between the critical Mach number and Mach 1 where drag increases rapidly.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The rapid increase in drag led aerodynamicists and aviators to disagree on whether supersonic flight was achievable until the sound barrier was broken in 1947 using the Bell X-1 aircraft.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] By the time the sound barrier was broken, aerodynamicists' understanding of the subsonic and low supersonic flow had matured.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The Cold War prompted the design of an ever-evolving line of high-performance aircraft.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Computational fluid dynamics began as an effort to solve for flow properties around complex objects and has rapidly grown to the point where entire aircraft can be designed using computer software, with wind-tunnel tests followed by flight tests to confirm the computer predictions.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Understanding of supersonic and hypersonic aerodynamics has matured since the 1960s, and the goals of aerodynamicists have shifted from the behaviour of fluid flow to the engineering of a vehicle such that it interacts predictably with the fluid flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Understanding the motion of air around an object (often called a flow field) enables the calculation of forces and moments acting on the object.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In many aerodynamics problems, the forces of interest are the fundamental forces of flight: lift, drag, thrust, and weight.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Of these, lift and drag are aerodynamic forces, i.e. forces due to air flow over a solid body.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Calculation of these quantities is often founded upon the assumption that the flow field behaves as a continuum.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Continuum flow fields are characterized by properties such as flow velocity, pressure, density, and temperature, which may be functions of position and time.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] These properties may be directly or indirectly measured in aerodynamics experiments or calculated starting with the equations for conservation of mass, momentum, and energy in air flows.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Density, flow velocity, and an additional property, viscosity, are used to classify flow fields.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Flow velocity is used to classify flows according to speed regime.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Subsonic flows are flow fields in which the air speed field is always below the local speed of sound.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Transonic flows include both regions of subsonic flow and regions in which the local flow speed is greater than the local speed of sound.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Supersonic flows are defined to be flows in which the flow speed is greater than the speed of sound everywhere.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] A fourth classification, hypersonic flow, refers to flows where the flow speed is much greater than the speed of sound.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Aerodynamicists disagree on the precise definition of hypersonic flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Compressible flow accounts for varying density within the flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Subsonic flows are often idealized as incompressible, i.e. the density is assumed to be constant.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Transonic and supersonic flows are compressible, and calculations that neglect the changes of density in these flow fields will yield inaccurate results.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Viscosity is associated with the frictional forces in a flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In some flow fields, viscous effects are very small, and approximate solutions may safely neglect viscous effects.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] These approximations are called inviscid flows.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Flows for which viscosity is not neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Finally, aerodynamic problems may also be classified by the flow environment.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] External aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes (e.g. around an airplane wing), while internal aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages inside solid objects (e.g. through a jet engine).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Unlike liquids and solids, gases are composed of discrete molecules which occupy only a small fraction of the volume filled by the gas.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] On a molecular level, flow fields are made up of the collisions of many individual gas molecules among themselves, and their collisions with solid surfaces.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] However, in most aerodynamics applications, the discrete molecular nature of gases is ignored, and the flow field is assumed to behave as a continuum.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] This assumption allows fluid properties such as density and flow velocity to be defined everywhere within the flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The validity of the continuum assumption is dependent on the density of the gas and the application in question.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] For the continuum assumption to be valid, the mean free path length must be much smaller than the length scale of the application in question.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] For example, many aerodynamics applications deal with aircraft flying in atmospheric conditions, where the mean free path length is on the order of micrometers and where the body is orders of magnitude larger.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In these cases, the length scale of the aircraft ranges from a few meters to a few tens of meters, which is much larger than the mean free path length.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] For such applications, the continuum assumption is reasonable.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The continuum assumption is less valid for extremely low-density flows like those encountered by vehicles at very high altitudes (e.g.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] 300,000 ft/90 km) or satellites in Low Earth orbit.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In these cases, statistical mechanics is a more accurate method of solving the problem than is continuum aerodynamics.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The Knudsen number can be used to guide the choice between statistical mechanics and the continuous formulation of aerodynamics.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The assumption of a fluid continuum allows problems in aerodynamics to be solved using fluid dynamics conservation laws.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Together, the equations are known as Navier–Stokes equations, although some authors define the term to only include the momentum equation(s).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Navier–Stokes equations have no known analytical solution and are solved in modern aerodynamics using computational techniques.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Because computational methods using high speed computers were not historically available and the high computational cost of solving these complex equations now that they are available, simplifications of the Navier–Stokes equations have been and continue to be employed.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Euler equations are a set of similar conservation equations which neglect viscosity and may be used in cases where the effect of viscosity is expected to be small.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Further simplifications lead to Laplace's equation and potential flow theory.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Additionally, Bernoulli's equation is a solution in one dimension to both the momentum and energy conservation equations.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The ideal gas law or another such equation of state is often used in conjunction with these equations to form a determined system which allows the solution for the unknown variables.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Aerodynamic problems are classified by the flow environment or properties of the flow, including flow speed, compressibility, and viscosity.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] *External* aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Evaluating the lift and drag on an airplane or the shock waves that form in front of the nose of a rocket are examples of external aerodynamics.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] *Internal* aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages in solid objects.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] For instance, internal aerodynamics encompasses the study of the airflow through a jet engine or through an air conditioning pipe.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Aerodynamic problems can also be classified according to whether the flow speed is below, near or above the speed of sound.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Aerodynamicists disagree over the precise definition of hypersonic flow; a rough definition considers flows with Mach numbers above 5 to be hypersonic.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The influence of viscosity on the flow dictates a third classification.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Some problems may encounter only very small viscous effects, in that case viscosity can be considered to be negligible.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The approximations to these problems are called inviscid flows.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Flows for which viscosity cannot be neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] An incompressible flow is a flow in which density is constant in both time and space.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Although all real fluids are compressible, a flow is often approximated as incompressible if the effect of the density changes cause only small changes to the calculated results.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] This is more likely to be true when the flow speeds are significantly lower than the speed of sound.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Effects of compressibility are more significant at speeds close to or above the speed of sound.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The Mach number is used to evaluate whether the incompressibility can be assumed, otherwise the effects of compressibility must be included.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Subsonic (or low-speed) aerodynamics describes fluid motion in flows which are much lower than the speed of sound everywhere in the flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] There are several branches of subsonic flow but one special case arises when the flow is inviscid, incompressible and irrotational.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] This case is called potential flow and allows the differential equations which describe the flow to be a simplified version of the equations of fluid dynamics, thus making available to the aerodynamicist a range of quick and easy solutions.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In solving a subsonic problem, one decision to be made by the aerodynamicist is whether to incorporate the effects of compressibility.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Compressibility is a description of the amount of change of density in the flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] When the effects of compressibility on the solution are small, the assumption that density is constant may be made.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The problem is then an incompressible low-speed aerodynamics problem.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] When the density is allowed to vary, the flow is called compressible.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In air, compressibility effects are usually ignored when the Mach number in the flow does not exceed 0.3 (about 335 feet (102 m) per second or 228 miles (366 km) per hour at 60 °F (16 °C)).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Above Mach 0.3, the problem flow should be described using compressible aerodynamics.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] According to the theory of aerodynamics, a flow is considered to be compressible if the density changes along a streamline.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] This means that–unlike incompressible flow–changes in density are considered.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In general, this is the case where the Mach number in part or all of the flow exceeds 0.3.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The Mach 0.3 value is rather arbitrary, but it is used because gas flows with a Mach number below that value demonstrate changes in density of less than 5%.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Furthermore, that maximum 5% density change occurs at the stagnation point (the point on the object where flow speed is zero), while the density changes around the rest of the object will be significantly lower.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Transonic, supersonic, and hypersonic flows are all compressible flows.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The term Transonic refers to a range of flow velocities just below and above the local speed of sound (generally taken as Mach 0.8–1.2).
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] It is defined as the range of speeds between the critical Mach number, when some parts of the airflow over an aircraft become supersonic, and a higher speed, typically near Mach 1.2, when all of the airflow is supersonic.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Between these speeds, some of the airflow is supersonic, while some of the airflow is not supersonic.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Supersonic aerodynamic problems are those involving flow speeds greater than the speed of sound.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Calculating the lift on the Concorde during cruise can be an example of a supersonic aerodynamic problem.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Supersonic flow behaves very differently from subsonic flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Fluids react to differences in pressure; pressure changes are how a fluid is "told" to respond to its environment.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Therefore, since sound is in fact, an infinitesimal pressure difference propagating through a fluid, the speed of sound in that fluid can be considered the fastest speed that "information" can travel in the flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] This difference most obviously manifests itself in the case of a fluid striking an object.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In front of that object, the fluid builds up a stagnation pressure as impact with the object brings the moving fluid to rest.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In fluid traveling at subsonic speed, this pressure disturbance can propagate upstream, changing the flow pattern ahead of the object and giving the impression that the fluid "knows" the object is there by seemingly adjusting its movement and is flowing around it.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In a supersonic flow, however, the pressure disturbance cannot propagate upstream.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Thus, when the fluid finally reaches the object it strikes it and the fluid is forced to change its properties – temperature, density, pressure, and Mach number—in an extremely violent and irreversible fashion called a shock wave.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The presence of shock waves, along with the compressibility effects of high-flow velocity (see Reynolds number) fluids, is the central difference between the supersonic and subsonic aerodynamics regimes.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In aerodynamics, hypersonic speeds are speeds that are highly supersonic.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In the 1970s, the term generally came to refer to speeds of Mach 5 (5 times the speed of sound) and above.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The hypersonic regime is a subset of the supersonic regime.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Hypersonic flow is characterized by high temperature flow behind a shock wave, viscous interaction, and chemical dissociation of gas.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The incompressible and compressible flow regimes produce many associated phenomena, such as boundary layers and turbulence.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The concept of a boundary layer is important in many problems in aerodynamics.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The viscosity and fluid friction in the air is approximated as being significant only in this thin layer.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] This assumption makes the description of such aerodynamics much more tractable mathematically.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] In aerodynamics, turbulence is characterized by chaotic property changes in the flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] These include low momentum diffusion, high momentum convection, and rapid variation of pressure and flow velocity in space and time.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Flow that is not turbulent is called laminar flow.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Aerodynamics is a significant element of vehicle design, including road cars and trucks where the main goal is to reduce the vehicle drag coefficient, and racing cars, where in addition to reducing drag the goal is also to increase the overall level of downforce.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Aerodynamics is also important in the prediction of forces and moments acting on sailing vessels.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] It is used in the design of mechanical components such as hard drive heads.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Structural engineers resort to aerodynamics, and particularly aeroelasticity, when calculating wind loads in the design of large buildings, bridges, and wind turbines.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The aerodynamics of internal passages is important in heating/ventilation, gas piping, and in automotive engines where detailed flow patterns strongly affect the performance of the engine.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Urban aerodynamics are studied by town planners and designers seeking to improve amenity in outdoor spaces, or in creating urban microclimates to reduce the effects of urban pollution.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] The field of environmental aerodynamics describes ways in which atmospheric circulation and flight mechanics affect ecosystems.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Aerodynamic equations are used in numerical weather prediction.
[src:aircraft/aerodynamic] Sports in which aerodynamics are of crucial importance include soccer, table tennis, cricket, baseball, and golf, in which most players can control the trajectory of the ball using the "Magnus effect".
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] An **airfoil** (American English) or **aerofoil** (British English) is a streamlined body that is capable of generating significantly more lift than drag.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Wings, sails and propeller blades are examples of airfoils.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Foils which work in a similar way submerged in water are called hydrofoils.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] When oriented at a suitable angle, a solid body moving through a fluid deflects the passing fluid, resulting in a force on the airfoil in the direction opposite to the deflection.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] This force is known as an aerodynamic force and can be resolved into two components: lift (perpendicular to the freestream velocity) and drag (parallel to the freestream velocity).
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] The lift on an airfoil is primarily the result of its angle of attack.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Most foil shapes require a positive angle of attack to generate lift, but cambered airfoils can generate lift at zero angle of attack.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Airfoils have different shapes for different speeds: those for subsonic flight have a rounded leading edge, while those for supersonic flight tend to be slimmer.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] The deflection of air by an airfoil generates a lower-pressure region above and behind itself.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] This pressure difference is accompanied by a velocity difference, as explained by Bernoulli's principle, so the resulting flowfield about the airfoil has a higher average velocity on the upper surface than on the lower surface.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] In some situations (e.g., inviscid potential flow) the lift force can be related directly to the average top/bottom velocity difference without computing the pressure by using the concept of circulation and the Kutta–Joukowski theorem.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] The wings and stabilizers of fixed-wing aircraft, as well as helicopter rotor blades, are built with airfoil-shaped cross sections.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Airfoils are also found in propellers, fans, compressors and turbines.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Sails are also airfoils, and the underwater surfaces of sailboats, such as the centerboard, rudder, and keel, are similar in cross-section and operate on the same principles as airfoils.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Swimming and flying creatures and even many plants and sessile organisms employ airfoils/hydrofoils, common examples being bird wings, the bodies of fish, and the shape of sand dollars.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] An airfoil-shaped wing can create downforce on an automobile or other motor vehicle, improving traction.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] When the wind is obstructed by an object such as a flat plate, a building, or the deck of a bridge, the object will experience drag and also an aerodynamic force perpendicular to the wind.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] This does not mean the object qualifies as an airfoil.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Airfoils are highly-efficient lifting shapes, able to generate more lift than similarly sized flat plates of the same area, and able to generate lift with significantly less drag.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Airfoils are used in the design of aircraft, propellers, rotor blades, wind turbines and other applications of aeronautical engineering.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] A lift and drag curve obtained in wind tunnel testing is shown on the right.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] The curve represents an airfoil with a positive camber so some lift is produced at zero angle of attack.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] With increased angle of attack, lift increases in a roughly linear relation, called the *slope* of the lift curve.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] At about 18 degrees this airfoil stalls, and lift falls off quickly beyond that.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] The drop in lift can be explained by the action of the upper-surface boundary layer, which separates and greatly thickens over the upper surface at and past the stall angle.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] The thickened boundary layer's displacement thickness changes the airfoil's effective shape, in particular it reduces its effective camber, which modifies the overall flow field so as to reduce the circulation and the lift.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] The thicker boundary layer also causes a large increase in pressure drag, so that the overall drag increases sharply near and past the stall point.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Airfoil design is a major facet of aerodynamics.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Various airfoils serve different flight regimes.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Asymmetric airfoils can generate lift at zero angle of attack, while a symmetric airfoil may better suit frequent inverted flight as in an aerobatic airplane.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] In the region of the ailerons and near a wingtip a symmetric airfoil can be used to increase the range of angles of attack to avoid spin–stall.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Thus a large range of angles can be used without boundary layer separation.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Subsonic airfoils have a round leading edge, which is naturally insensitive to the angle of attack.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] The cross section is not strictly circular, however: the radius of curvature is increased before the wing achieves maximum thickness to minimize the chance of boundary layer separation.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] This elongates the wing and moves the point of maximum thickness back from the leading edge.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Supersonic airfoils are much more angular in shape and can have a very sharp leading edge, which is very sensitive to angle of attack.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] A supercritical airfoil has its maximum thickness close to the leading edge to have a lot of length to slowly shock the supersonic flow back to subsonic speeds.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Generally such transonic airfoils and also the supersonic airfoils have a low camber to reduce drag divergence.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Modern aircraft wings may have different airfoil sections along the wing span, each one optimized for the conditions in each section of the wing.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Movable high-lift devices, flaps and sometimes slats, are fitted to airfoils on almost every aircraft.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] A trailing edge flap acts similarly to an aileron; however, it, as opposed to an aileron, can be retracted partially into the wing if not used.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] For many wings, the boundary layer of the air flow close to the upper surface rapidly becomes turbulent past the maximum thickness point, which increases the skin friction drag.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] A **laminar flow wing** moves the maximum thickness point well back along the chord from a typical 25% chord position from to 60% from the leading edge or more.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] This maintains smooth laminar flow over a larger percentage of the wing and significantly reduces drag.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] However, surface contamination will disrupt the boundary layer, making it turbulent.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Insects, for example, impacting and sticking onto the wing will cause the loss of wedge shaped regions of laminar flow across the wing's surface.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] This is a particular problem for aircraft with high take off speeds, since many insects are found near the ground making it unlikely that laminar flow can be sustained into the flight.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Gliders have seen widespread uptake of laminar flow airfoils due to their low speeds and need for low drag aerodynamic structures.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] NASA's research in the 1980s revealed the practicality and usefulness of laminar flow wing designs and opened the way for laminar-flow applications on modern practical aircraft surfaces, from subsonic general aviation aircraft to transonic large transport aircraft, to supersonic designs.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Schemes have been devised to define airfoils – an example is the NACA system.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Various airfoil generation systems are also used.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] An example of a general purpose airfoil that finds wide application, and pre–dates the NACA system, is the Clark-Y.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Today, airfoils can be designed for specific functions by the use of computer programs.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Some important parameters to describe an airfoil's shape are its *camber* and its *thickness*.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] For example, an airfoil of the NACA 4-digit series such as the NACA 2415 (to be read as 2 – 4 – 15) describes an airfoil with a camber of 0.02 chord located at 0.40 chord, with 0.15 chord of maximum thickness.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] In two-dimensional flow around a uniform wing of infinite span, the slope of the lift curve is determined primarily by the *trailing edge angle*.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] The slope is greatest if the angle is zero; and decreases as the angle increases.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] For a wing of finite span, the aspect ratio of the wing also significantly influences the slope of the curve.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] As aspect ratio decreases, the slope also decreases.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] 2. on a cambered airfoil, the aerodynamic center lies exactly one quarter of the chord behind the leading edge, but the position of the center of pressure moves when the angle of attack changes.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] 3. the slope of the *lift coefficient versus angle of attack* line is $2\pi \!$ units per radian.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] is the section lift coefficient when the angle of attack is zero.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Thin airfoil theory assumes the air is an inviscid fluid so does not account for the stall of the airfoil, which usually occurs at an angle of attack between 10° and 15° for typical airfoils.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] In the mid-late 2000s, however, a theory predicting the onset of leading-edge stall was proposed by Wallace J.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Morris's subsequent refinements contain the details on the current state of theoretical knowledge on the leading-edge stall phenomenon.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Morris's theory predicts the critical angle of attack for leading-edge stall onset as the condition at which a global separation zone is predicted in the solution for the inner flow.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Morris's theory demonstrates that a subsonic flow about a thin airfoil can be described in terms of an outer region, around most of the airfoil chord, and an inner region, around the nose, that asymptotically match each other.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] As the flow in the outer region is dominated by classical thin airfoil theory, Morris's equations exhibit many components of thin airfoil theory.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] In thin airfoil theory, the width of the (2D) airfoil is assumed negligible, and the airfoil itself replaced with a 1D blade along its camber line, oriented at the angle of attack α.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Let the position along the blade be x, ranging from 0 at the wing's front to c at the trailing edge; the camber of the airfoil, *dy*⁄*dx*, is assumed sufficiently small that one need not distinguish between x and position relative to the fuselage.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] The flow across the airfoil generates a circulation around the blade, which can be modeled as a vortex sheet of position-varying strength γ(*x*).
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] The Kutta condition implies that γ(*c*)=0, but the strength is singular at the bladefront, with γ(*x*)∝1⁄√*x* for *x* ≈ 0.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] From the Biot–Savart law, the vorticity γ(*x*) produces a flow field $w(x)={\frac {1}{2\pi }}\int _{0}^{c}{\frac {\gamma (x')}{x-x'}}\,dx'{\text{,}}$ oriented normal to the airfoil at x.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] Since the airfoil is an impermeable surface, the flow $w(x)$ must balance an inverse flow from V.
[src:aircraft/aerofoil] By the small-angle approximation, V is inclined at angle α-*dy*⁄*dx* relative to the blade at position x, and the normal component is correspondingly (α-*dy*⁄*dx*)*V*.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] A significant part of **aeronautical science** is a branch of dynamics called aerodynamics, which deals with the motion of air and the way that it interacts with objects in motion, such as an aircraft.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Attempts to fly without any real aeronautical understanding have been made from the earliest times, typically by constructing wings and jumping from a tower with crippling or lethal results.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Wiser investigators sought to gain some rational understanding through the study of bird flight.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Medieval Islamic Golden Age scientists such as Abbas ibn Firnas also made such studies.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] The founders of modern aeronautics, Leonardo da Vinci in the Renaissance and Cayley in 1799, both began their investigations with studies of bird flight.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Man-carrying kites are believed to have been used extensively in ancient China.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] In 1282 the Italian explorer Marco Polo described the Chinese techniques then current.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] The Chinese also constructed small hot air balloons, or lanterns, and rotary-wing toys.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] An early European to provide any scientific discussion of flight was Roger Bacon, who described principles of operation for the lighter-than-air balloon and the flapping-wing ornithopter, which he envisaged would be constructed in the future.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] The lifting medium for his balloon would be an "aether" whose composition he did not know.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] In the late fifteenth century, Leonardo da Vinci followed up his study of birds with designs for some of the earliest flying machines, including the flapping-wing ornithopter and the rotating-wing helicopter.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Although his designs were rational, they were not based on particularly good science.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Many of his designs, such as a four-person screw-type helicopter, have severe flaws.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Da Vinci's work was lost after his death and did not reappear until it had been overtaken by the work of George Cayley.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] The modern era of lighter-than-air flight began early in the 17th century with Galileo's experiments in which he showed that air has weight.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Around 1650 Cyrano de Bergerac wrote some fantasy novels in which he described the principle of ascent using a substance (dew) he supposed to be lighter than air, and descending by releasing a controlled amount of the substance.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Francesco Lana de Terzi measured the pressure of air at sea level and in 1670 proposed the first scientifically credible lifting medium in the form of hollow metal spheres from which all the air had been pumped out.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] These would be lighter than the displaced air and able to lift an airship.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] His proposed methods of controlling height are still in use today; by carrying ballast which may be dropped overboard to gain height, and by venting the lifting containers to lose height.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] In practice de Terzi's spheres would have collapsed under air pressure, and further developments had to wait for more practicable lifting gases.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] From the mid-18th century the Montgolfier brothers in France began experimenting with balloons.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Their balloons were made of paper, and early experiments using steam as the lifting gas were short-lived due to its effect on the paper as it condensed.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Meanwhile, the discovery of hydrogen led Joseph Black in c.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] 1780 to propose its use as a lifting gas, though practical demonstration awaited a gas-tight balloon material.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] On hearing of the Montgolfier Brothers' invitation, the French Academy member Jacques Charles offered a similar demonstration of a hydrogen balloon.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Charles and two craftsmen, the Robert brothers, developed a gas-tight material of rubberised silk for the envelope.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] The hydrogen gas was to be generated by chemical reaction during the filling process.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] The Montgolfier designs had several shortcomings, not least the need for dry weather and a tendency for sparks from the fire to set light to the paper balloon.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] The manned design had a gallery around the base of the balloon rather than the hanging basket of the first, unmanned design, which brought the paper closer to the fire.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] On their free flight, De Rozier and d'Arlandes took buckets of water and sponges to douse these fires as they arose.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] On the other hand, the manned design of Charles was essentially modern.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] As a result of these exploits, the hot air balloon became known as the *Montgolfière* type and the gas balloon the *Charlière*.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Charles and the Robert brothers' next balloon, *La Caroline*, was a Charlière that followed Jean Baptiste Meusnier's proposals for an elongated dirigible balloon, and was notable for having an outer envelope with the gas contained in a second, inner ballonet.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] On 19 September 1784, it completed the first flight of over 100 kilometres (62 mi), between Paris and Beuvry, despite the man-powered propulsive devices proving useless.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] The balloon envelope was made of goldbeater's skin.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] The first flight ended in disaster and the approach has seldom been used since.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Sir George Cayley (1773–1857) is widely acknowledged as the founder of modern aeronautics.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] He was first called the "father of the aeroplane" in 1846 and Henson called him the "father of aerial navigation." He was the first true scientific aerial investigator to publish his work, which included for the first time the underlying principles and forces of flight.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] In 1809 he began the publication of a landmark three-part treatise titled "On Aerial Navigation" (1809–1810).
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] He developed the modern conventional form of the fixed-wing aeroplane having a stabilising tail with both horizontal and vertical surfaces, flying gliders both unmanned and manned.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] He introduced the use of the whirling arm test rig to investigate the aerodynamics of flight, using it to discover the benefits of the curved or cambered aerofoil over the flat wing he had used for his first glider.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] He also identified and described the importance of dihedral, diagonal bracing and drag reduction, and contributed to the understanding and design of ornithopters and parachutes.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Another significant invention was the tension-spoked wheel, which he devised in order to create a light, strong wheel for aircraft undercarriage.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] During the 19th century, Cayley's ideas were further developed, tested, and formalised.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Public and scientific interest in aeronautics grew during the Victorian era, with notable contributions from figures such as John Stringfellow, James Glaisher, Francis Wenham, and Frederick Brearey.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Wenham, Glaisher, and Brearey co-founded the Aeronautical Society of Great Britain in 1866, together with the 8th Duke of Argyll.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Although aeronautical research at the time remained largely experimental, the Society played an important role in promoting heavier-than-air flight, including through the First Aeronautical Exhibition held in 1868 at The Crystal Palace.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] These developments, along with growing international interest, helped lay the groundwork for the later work of Horatio Phillips among others, but more importantly of Otto Lilienthal, a German engineer and businessman who became known as the "flying man".
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] He was the first person to make well-documented, repeated, successful flights with gliders, therefore making the idea of "heavier than air" a reality.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Newspapers and magazines published photographs of Lilienthal gliding, favourably influencing public and scientific opinion about the possibility of flying machines becoming practical.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] His work led to the development of the modern wing.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] His flight attempts in Berlin in the year 1891 are seen as the beginning of human flight and the "Lilienthal Normalsegelapparat" is considered to be the first air plane in series production, making the *Maschinenfabrik Otto Lilienthal* in Berlin the first air plane production company in the world.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Otto Lilienthal is often referred to as either the "father of aviation" or "father of flight".
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Aeronautics may be divided into three main branches, Aviation, Aeronautical science and Aeronautical engineering.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Aviation is the art or practice of aeronautics.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Historically aviation meant only heavier-than-air flight, but nowadays it includes flying in balloons and airships.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Aeronautical engineering covers the design and construction of aircraft, including how they are powered, how they are used and how they are controlled for safe operation.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] A major part of aeronautical engineering is aerodynamics, the science of passing through the air.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] With the increasing activity in space flight, nowadays aeronautics and astronautics are often combined as aerospace engineering.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] The science of aerodynamics deals with the motion of air and the way that it interacts with objects in motion, such as an aircraft.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] A rocket or rocket vehicle is a missile, spacecraft, aircraft or other vehicle which obtains thrust from a rocket engine.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] In all rockets, the exhaust is formed entirely from propellants carried within the rocket before use.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Rocket engines work by action and reaction.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Rocket engines push rockets forwards simply by throwing their exhaust backwards extremely fast.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Rockets for military and recreational uses date back to at least 13th-century China.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Significant scientific, interplanetary and industrial use did not occur until the 20th century, when rocketry was the enabling technology of the Space Age, including setting foot on the Moon.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Rockets are used for fireworks, weaponry, ejection seats, launch vehicles for artificial satellites, human spaceflight and exploration of other planets.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] While comparatively inefficient for low speed use, they are very lightweight and powerful, capable of generating large accelerations and of attaining extremely high speeds with reasonable efficiency.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Chemical rockets are the most common type of rocket and they typically create their exhaust by the combustion of rocket propellant.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] Chemical rockets store a large amount of energy in an easily released form, and can be very dangerous.
[src:aircraft/aeronautics] However, careful design, testing, construction and use minimizes risks.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] An **aircraft** is a vehicle that can fly by gaining support from the air.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] It counters the force of gravity by using either static lift or the dynamic lift of an airfoil, or, in a few cases, direct downward thrust from its engines.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Common examples of aircraft include airplanes, drones, rotorcraft (including helicopters), airships (including blimps), gliders, paramotors, and hot air balloons.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Part 1 (Definitions and Abbreviations) of Subchapter A of Chapter I of Title 14 of the U.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Code of Federal Regulations states that *aircraft* "means a device that is used or intended to be used for flight in the air".
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The human activity that surrounds aircraft is called *aviation*.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The science of aviation includes the designing and building of aircraft, which is called *aeronautics*. a *crewed* aircraft is flown by an onboard pilot, whereas an unmanned aerial vehicle may be remotely controlled or *autonomous*, controlled by onboard computers.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Aircraft may be classified by different criteria, such as lift type, propulsion (if any), usage and others.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The history of aviation spans over two millennia, from the earliest innovations like kites and attempts at tower jumping to supersonic and hypersonic flight in powered, heavier-than-air jet aircraft.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Kite flying in China, dating back several hundred years BC, is considered the earliest example of man-made flight.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] In the 15th century, Leonardo da Vinci created flying machine designs incorporating aeronautical concepts, but they were unworkable due to the limitations of contemporary knowledge.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] In the late 18th century, the Montgolfier brothers invented the hot-air balloon which soon led to manned flights.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] At almost the same time, the discovery of hydrogen gas led to the invention of the hydrogen balloon.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Various theories in mechanics by physicists during the same period, such as fluid dynamics and Newton's laws of motion, led to the development of modern aerodynamics; most notably by Sir George Cayley.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Balloons, both free-flying and tethered, began to be used for military purposes from the end of the 18th century, with France establishing balloon companies during the French Revolution.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] In the 19th century, especially the second half, experiments with gliders provided the basis for learning the dynamics of winged aircraft; most notably by Cayley, Otto Lilienthal, and Octave Chanute.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] By the early 20th century, advances in engine technology and aerodynamics made controlled, powered, manned heavier-than-air flight possible for the first time.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] In 1903, following their pioneering research and experiments with wing design and aircraft control, the Wright brothers successfully incorporated all of the required elements to create and fly the first airplane.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] In 1906 Charles Frederick Page was granted the first U.S. patent for an aircraft.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The basic configuration with its characteristic cruciform tail was established by 1909, followed by rapid design and performance improvements aided by the development of more powerful engines.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The first vessels of the air were the rigid steerable balloons pioneered by Ferdinand von Zeppelin that became synonymous with airships and dominated long-distance flight until the 1930s, when large flying boats became popular for trans-oceanic routes.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] After World War II, the flying boats were in turn replaced by airplanes operating from land, made far more capable first by improved propeller engines, then by jet engines, which revolutionized both civilian air travel and military aviation.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] In the latter half of the 20th century, the development of digital electronics led to major advances in flight instrumentation and "fly-by-wire" systems.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The 21st century has seen the widespread use of pilotless drones for military, commercial, and recreational purposes.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] With computerized controls, inherently unstable aircraft designs, such as flying wings, have also become practical.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Lighter-than-air aircraft or *aerostats* use buoyancy to float in the air in much the same way that ships float on the water.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] They are characterized by one or more large cells or canopies, filled with a lifting gas such as helium, hydrogen or hot air, which is less dense than the surrounding air.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Other gases lighter than air also theoretically work; however, such gases also need to be safe for human use (non-flammable, non-toxic).
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Small hot-air balloons, called sky lanterns, were first invented in ancient China prior to the 3rd century BC and used primarily in cultural celebrations, although they also had military purposes.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] They, along with kites, were two forms of unmanned aircraft that originated from China.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Kites were also used in the military, but unlike sky lanterns, their flight is caused by the differences in air pressure beneath and above the kite.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] A balloon was originally any aerostat, while the term airship was used for large, powered aircraft designs—usually fixed-wing.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] In 1919, Frederick Handley Page was reported as referring to "ships of the air," with smaller passenger types as "Air yachts." In the 1930s, large intercontinental flying boats were also sometimes referred to as "ships of the air" or "flying-ships".
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Lighter-than-air aircraft don't typically require a pilot's license in the United States.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] In most countries in Europe, standards for flying Lighter-than-air aircraft tend to be stricter compared to the United States.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Heavier-than-air aircraft or *aerodynes* are denser than air and thus must find some way to obtain enough lift that can overcome the aircraft's weight.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] There are two ways to produce dynamic upthrust—aerodynamic lift by having air flowing past an aerofoil (such dynamic interaction of aerofoils with air is the origin of the term "aerodyne"), or powered lift in the form of reactional lift from downward engine thrust.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Aerodynamic lift involving wings is the most common, and can be achieved via two methods.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Fixed-wing aircraft (airplanes and gliders) achieve airflow past the wings by having the entire aircraft moving forward through the air, while rotorcraft (helicopters and autogyros) do so by having mobile, elongated wings spinning rapidly around a mast in an assembly known as the rotor.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Gliders were one of the first forms of a fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] They are a special type of aircraft that doesn't require an engine.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The first person to successfully build a human-carrying glider was George Cayley, who also was the first to discover the four major aerodynamic forces.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The first powered aircraft (Airplane) was invented by Wilbur and Orville Wright.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] A *rotary-wing aircraft*, *rotorwing aircraft* or *rotorcraft* is a heavier-than-air aircraft with rotary wings that spin around a vertical mast to generate lift.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The assembly of several rotor blades mounted on a single mast is referred to as a rotor.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) defines a rotorcraft as "supported in flight by the reactions of the air on one or more rotors".
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Rotorcraft generally include aircraft where one or more rotors provide lift throughout the entire flight, such as helicopters, gyroplanes, autogyros, and gyrodynes.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Compound rotorcraft augment the rotor with additional thrust engines, propellers, or static lifting surfaces.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Some types, such as helicopters, are capable of vertical takeoff and landing.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] An aircraft that uses rotor lift for vertical flight but changes to solely fixed-wing lift in horizontal flight is not a rotorcraft but a convertiplane.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The largest aircraft by weight and largest regular fixed-wing aircraft ever built, as of 2016, was the Antonov An-225 *Mriya*.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] That Soviet-built (Ukrainian SSR) six-engine transport of the 1980s was 84 m (276 ft) long, with an 88 m (289 ft) wingspan.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] It holds the world payload record, after transporting 428,834 lb (194,516 kg) of goods, and has flown 100 t (220,000 lb) loads commercially.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] With a maximum loaded weight of 550–700 t (1,210,000–1,540,000 lb), it was also the heaviest aircraft built to date.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The aircraft was destroyed during the Russo-Ukrainian War.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The largest military airplanes are the Ukrainian Antonov An-124 *Ruslan* (world's second-largest airplane, also used as a civilian transport), and American Lockheed C-5 Galaxy transport, weighing, loaded, over 380 t (840,000 lb).
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The fastest recorded powered aircraft flight and fastest recorded aircraft flight of an air-breathing powered aircraft was of the NASA X-43A *Pegasus*, a scramjet-powered, hypersonic, lifting body experimental research aircraft, at Mach 9.68 or 6,755 mph (10,870 km/h) on 16 November 2004.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Before the X-43A, the fastest recorded powered airplane flight, and still the record for the fastest manned powered airplane, was the North American X-15, rocket-powered airplane at Mach 6.7 or 7,274 km/h (4,520 mph) on 3 October 1967.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The fastest manned, air-breathing powered airplane is the Lockheed SR-71 Blackbird, a U.S. reconnaissance jet fixed-wing aircraft, having reached 3,530 km/h (2,193 mph) on 28 July 1976.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The main feature of unpowered aircraft is the inability to directly provide thrust through its engines.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] This means that all unpowered aircraft rely on the environment for sustained flight.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Gliders, for example, take advantage of their aerodynamic properties to enable them to travel long distances.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Techniques such as thermal circling, where gliders fly into warm air which allows them to rise, prolong flight time.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Due to the lack of an engine, initial propulsion assistance is usually necessary to ensure flight.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] A common glider launching method is aerotowing, where another aircraft tows the glider to an altitude from which sustained flight is possible.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Steering for a glider is also rudimentary, while more complex gliders like sailplanes usually have joysticks for steering, more basic aircraft like hang gliders rely on the pilot's physical coordination to change the centre of gravity.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] A powered aircraft is an aircraft with a source of mechanical power, used to produce thrust.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Such sources are generally engines, as is the case with airplanes, but can be human-powered in more extreme cases.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Propeller aircraft, as their name suggests, rely on propellers to produce thrust for the airplane.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Compared to engines using propellers, jet engines can provide much higher thrust, higher speeds and, above about 40,000 ft (12,000 m), greater efficiency.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Although some rotorcraft, such as rotor kites, can be unpowered, most rotorcraft are powered by either piston engines or turboprops.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Some rotorcraft, including autogyros and gyrodynes, are propelled by a conventional propeller or jet engine, with the rotor unpowered, but most modern rotorcraft have a powered rotor, allowing them to hover in place.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Autogyros and gyrodynes are steered using a rudder, similarly to propeller and jet aircraft, and rotorcraft with powered rotors, such as helicopters, turn by adjusting the pitch of the rotor cyclically, so that the rotors on one side produce more lift than the other.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Rotorcraft with powered rotors typically need a tail rotor to counter the rotational torque produced by the rotor, which can cause the helicopter to spin.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] An *aerostat* or *lighter-than-air aircraft* relies on buoyancy to maintain flight.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Aerostats include unpowered balloons (free-flying or tethered) and powered airships.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The relative density of an aerostat as a whole is lower than that of the surrounding atmospheric air (hence the name "lighter-than-air").
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Its main component is one or more gas capsules made of lightweight skins, containing a lifting gas (hot air, or any gas with lower density than air, typically hydrogen or helium) that displaces a large volume of air to generate enough buoyancy to overcome its own weight.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Payload (passengers and cargo) can then be carried on attached components such as a basket, a gondola, a cabin or various hardpoints.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] With airships, which need to be able to fly against wind, the lifting gas capsules are often protected by a more rigid outer envelope or an airframe, with other gasbags such as ballonets to help modulate buoyancy.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Aerostats are so named because they use aerostatic buoyant force that does not require any forward movement through the surrounding air mass, resulting in the inherent ability to levitate and perform vertical takeoff and landing.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] This contrasts with the heavier-than-air aerodynes that primarily use aerodynamic lift, which must have consistent airflow over an aerofoil (wing) surface to stay airborne.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The term has also been used in a narrower sense, to refer to the statically tethered balloon in contrast to the free-flying airship.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] This article uses the term in its broader sense.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] An *aerodyne* is a heavier-than-air aircraft that relies on aerodynamic lift, or upthrust produced by the airflow, to fly.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Aerodynes include rotorcraft, airplanes, gliders, and several other varieties of aircraft.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Airplanes use wings, or airfoils, to direct the airflow to produce lift.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Wings are usually constructed with a wooden or metal inner framework, and a skin stretched over it.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Rotorcraft use a rotor which acts like a rotating wing, allowing them to hover in place.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] When aerodynes carry a payload, it is usually carried inside the aircraft's fuselage, or central structure, but aerodynes can also carry loads attached outside the aircraft or inside the wing.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Unlike aerostats, which control their altitude by changing their weight, aerodynes use control surfaces to control their altitude, or raise or lower the lift on their wing by adjusting their speed.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] As they typically travel at higher speeds than aerostats, most aerodynes have a rigid structure consisting of a frame covered by a skin.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Powered aircraft are typically powered by internal combustion engines (piston or turbine) burning fossil fuels—typically gasoline (avgas) or jet fuel.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] A very few are powered by rocket power, ramjet propulsion, or by electric motors, or by internal combustion engines of other types, or using other fuels.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] A very few have been powered, for short flights, by human muscle energy (e.g.: Gossamer Condor).
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The avionics comprise any *electronic* aircraft flight control systems and related equipment, including electronic cockpit instrumentation, navigation, radar, monitoring, and communications systems.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The flight envelope of an aircraft refers to its approved design capabilities in terms of airspeed, load factor and altitude.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The maximal total *range* is the maximum distance an aircraft can fly between takeoff and landing.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Powered aircraft range is limited by the aviation fuel energy storage capacity (chemical or electrical) considering both weight and volume limits.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Unpowered aircraft range depends on factors such as cross-country speed and environmental conditions.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The range can be seen as the cross-country ground speed multiplied by the maximum time in the air.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The fuel time limit for powered aircraft is fixed by the available fuel (considering reserve fuel requirements) and the rate of consumption.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The Airbus A350-900ULR is among the longest range airliners.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Some aircraft can gain energy while airborne through the environment (e.g. collecting solar energy or through rising air currents from mechanical or thermal lifting) or from in-flight refueling.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] These aircraft could theoretically have an infinite range.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Control systems adjust the orientation of a vehicle about its CG.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] A control system includes control surfaces which, when deflected, generate a moment (or couple from ailerons) about the cg which rotates the aircraft in pitch, roll, and yaw.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] For example, a pitching moment comes from a force applied at a distance forward or aft of the cg, causing the aircraft to pitch up or down.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] A fixed-wing aircraft increases or decreases the lift generated by the wings when it pitches nose up or down by increasing or decreasing the angle of attack (AOA).
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The roll angle is also known as bank angle on a fixed-wing aircraft, which usually "banks" to change the horizontal direction of flight.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] A fixed wing is typically unstable in pitch, roll, and yaw.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Pitch and yaw stabilities of conventional fixed wing designs require horizontal and vertical stabilisers, which act similarly to the feathers on an arrow.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] These stabilizing surfaces allow equilibrium of aerodynamic forces and to stabilise the flight dynamics of pitch and yaw.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] In fixed-wing aircraft, multiple control surfaces are used to adjust the aircraft's roll, pitch, and yaw.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Ailerons, hinged surfaces normally located on the rear edge of the wing, can raise or lower the lift produced by one side of the wing, causing the aircraft to bank to one side.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Elevators, usually located in the horizontal stabilizer, are used to increase or decrease the lift produced by the tail, causing the aircraft to pitch upwards or downwards, which in turn affects the lift of the wing.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] However, when the ailerons are used to turn an aircraft to the left, the right aileron must be tilted downwards, producing more drag than the left aileron and causing the aircraft to yaw right.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] To counteract this force, most fixed-wing aircraft have a rudder mounted on the vertical stabilizer which can deflect the airflow to the tail left or right to control the aircraft's yaw.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] In rotorcraft, control is mainly accomplished through the cyclical tilting of the rotor's blades, increasing the angle of attack of the blades on one side and decreasing the angle of attack on the other.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Similarly to the rudder on fixed-wing aircraft, rotorcraft with powered rotors have a tail rotor, which counters the rotational thrust produced by the rotor and allows the aircraft to turn in forward flight.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Rotorcraft with unpowered rotors, such as autogyros, use a rudder for yaw.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Aircraft engines produce gases, noise, and particulates from fossil fuel combustion, raising environmental concerns over their global effects and on local air quality.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Jet airliners contribute to climate change by emitting carbon dioxide (CO2), the best understood greenhouse gas, and, with less scientific understanding, nitrogen oxides, contrails and particulates.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Their radiative forcing is estimated at 1.4 that of CO2 alone, excluding induced cirrus cloud with a very low level of scientific understanding.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] In 2018, global commercial operations generated 2.4% of CO2 emissions.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Jet airliners have become more fuel efficient and CO2 emissions per revenue ton-kilometer (RTK) in 2018 were 47% of those in 1990.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] In 2018, CO2 emissions averaged 88 grams of CO2 per revenue passenger per km.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] While the aviation industry is more fuel efficient, overall emissions have risen as the volume of air travel has increased.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] By 2020, aviation emissions were 70% higher than in 2005 and they could grow by 300% by 2050.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Aircraft noise pollution disrupts sleep, children's education and could increase cardiovascular risk.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Airports can generate water pollution due to their extensive handling of jet fuel and deicing chemicals if not contained, contaminating nearby water bodies.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Aviation activities emit ozone and ultrafine particles, both of which are health hazards.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Piston engines used in general aviation burn Avgas, releasing toxic lead.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Aviation's environmental footprint can be reduced by better fuel economy in aircraft, or air traffic control and flight routes can be optimized to lower non-CO2 effects on climate from NOx, particulates or contrails.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Aviation biofuel, emissions trading and carbon offsetting, part of the ICAO's CORSIA, can lower CO2 emissions.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Aviation usage can be lowered by short-haul flight bans, train connections, personal choices and aviation taxation and subsidies.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Fuel-powered aircraft may be replaced by hybrid electric aircraft and electric aircraft or by hydrogen-powered aircraft.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Since 2021, the IATA members plan to achieve net-zero carbon emissions by 2050, followed by the ICAO in 2022.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] A military aircraft is any aircraft that is operated by a legal or insurrectionary armed service of any type.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Although scheduled air transport is the larger operation in terms of passenger numbers, GA is larger in the number of flights (and flight hours, in the U.S.) In the U.S., GA carries 166 million passengers each year, more than any individual airline, though less than all the airlines combined.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Since 2004, the U.S. airlines combined have carried over 600 million passengers each year, and in 2014, they carried a combined 662,819,232 passengers.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] All scheduled air transport is commercial, but general aviation can be either commercial or private.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Normally, the pilot, aircraft, and operator must all be authorized to perform commercial operations through separate commercial licensing, registration, and operation certificates.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] An *experimental aircraft* is an aircraft intended for testing new aerospace technologies and design concepts.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The term *research aircraft* or *testbed aircraft*, by contrast, generally denotes aircraft modified to perform scientific studies, such as weather research or geophysical surveying, similar to a research vessel.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] The term "experimental aircraft" also has specific legal meaning in Australia, the United States and some other countries; usually used to refer to aircraft flown with an experimental certificate.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] In the United States, this also includes most homebuilt aircraft, many of which are based on conventional designs and hence are experimental only in name because of certain restrictions in operation.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Model aircraft are typically small-scale replicas of flying aircraft, or new designs built smaller than most passenger aircraft.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Static model aircraft, which cannot fly, are usually not considered to be aircraft, but they can be used to test aspects of a flying aircraft, such as its aerodynamics.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Flying models are commonly propelled by electric motors, combustion engines, or are gliders, but there are many alternate methods of propulsion, such as wound rubber bands and small jet engines.
[src:aircraft/aircraft] Most flying model aircraft are either radio-controlled aircraft, fly freely, or are controlled by wires held by the pilot.
